Orero said children have high immunity because of the activities they engage in and that, after all, they have been active in tournaments and several activities and none of them has been adversely effected. 

“We are only praying that the ministry will listen to us because other activities have moved on. 

“We went through health protocols together with all our regional officials and we promise to abide by those protocols so that the activities can continue,” Orero said. 

According to him, there is no way teachers will implement the competency-based curriculum without co-curricular activities. 

He further argued that some of the children depend on co-curricular activities for their future livelihoods. 

“Now that the schools are back, there is no single reason that this activities should not go on but, as an association, we are seeking audience with the ministry so that we explain our part,”  Orero said. 



