The primary and secondary school games’ organisers suffered the huge blow Sunday after President Uhuru Kenyatta banned extra-curricular activities for the next three months. 

In the Executive Order signed yesterday, the president banned schools’ co-curricular activities like sports, drama, music and prize-giving for 90 days as well as all exchange visits between schools. 

KSSSA had lined up a bevy of activities for the year that would culminate in the country competing in the World School Games in Jinjiang, China, for the first time. 

The East Africa Secondary School Games were also due to return to Kenya after a four-year absence. 

When the first Covid-19 positive case was reported in the country on March 12, Term One Secondary Games were at county level as schools battled for slots for the national games. Last year, the duo were unable to hold a number of their championships. Dignitaries from International Schools Sports Federation and the World School Games had also confirmed attendance in the 19th edition of the championship. Pope Francis has accepted his resignation, which came after he attained the mandatory retirement age. Nyeri Town MP Mr Ngunjiri Wambugu said Mr Kang’ata was not sincere in his letter for sharing it with the media and the public. Learning institutions were shut in March to contain the spread of the coronavirus.